          "body": "The imprecatory psalms require careful canonical reading in light of the New Testament without dissolving their Old Testament meaning. Jesus quotes Psalm 69 (another imprecatory psalm) as messianic (John 15:25; Romans 15:3), and the souls under the altar in Revelation 6:10 cry 'How long, O Lord, holy and true, wilt You refrain from judging and avenging our blood?' — the imprecatory prayer is still being offered in heaven itself at the end of history. The New Testament does not abolish imprecatory prayer; it redirects and purifies it. Romans 12:19 — 'Never take your own revenge, beloved, but leave room for the wrath of God, for it is written, Vengeance is Mine, I will repay, says the Lord' — is the New Covenant form of Psalm 58's logic: do not execute it yourself; hand it to the Divine Court. Jesus on the cross could say 'Father, forgive them' (Luke 23:34) precisely because He was also 'the Lamb who takes away the sin of the world' (John 1:29) — at the cross, the imprecation fell on the Son so that forgiveness could be offered to sinners. The imprecatory psalms remind the church that forgiveness does not mean justice is bypassed; it means justice has already been satisfied at Calvary. The believer praying Psalm 58 today prays with one eye on the cross — where the ultimate judgment fell — and one eye on the second coming, where every hidden injustice will be exposed and every victim vindicated."
